sections.text:
Acute in vivo microdialysis was carried out on ChR2-(n = 3) and ChR2+ (n = 6) mice maintained under inhaled isoflurane (1-3%) anesthesia in a stereotaxic frame. Throughout the procedure, body temperature was maintained at 37 °C with an electric heating pad (CWE, Ardmore, PA). Mice were mounted on the stereotaxic frame and two burr holes were made in the skull: one above the MRN and one above the dHC. An optical (200 μm, 0.37 NA) connected to a 473 nm diode-pumped solid state laser (Laserglow), was lowered to the top of the MRN (Interaural: A/P −0.6, M/L 0, D/V +1. 75;and Franklin, 2001 ). A microdialysis probe (2 mm cuprophane membrane;
Products, Toronto, Ontario, Canada) was lowered into the (Bregma: A/P −2.0, M/L ± 1.2, D/V −2.75; Paxinos and Franklin, 2001) covering its entire dorso-ventral axis. The dialysis probe was continuously perfused with artificial cerebrospinal fluid (aCSF consisted of 145 mM NaCl, 2.7 mM KCl, 1.2 mM CaCl2, 1.0 mM MgCl2, and 2 mM phosphate buffer, pH 6.7) at 1 μl/min using a 1.0 ml gastight syringe and a syringe pump (CMA Microdialysis, Holliston, USA). Sampling began 90 min following probe insertion. Samples were continuously collected every 10 min and immediately analyzed for 5-HT concentration using high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC; see below) and electrochemical detection. Baseline 5-HT concentration was considered stable when three consecutive samples varied less than 10% from the previous sample (Baseline; 14 samples required on average). Once a stable baseline was achieved, MRN photostimulation (4 Hz, 10 ms pulse width, 10 mW) was applied for 10 min, after which photostimulation was terminated.
Measurement of 5-HT levels in dialysate samples was conducted on an analytical system consisting of an Antec Leyden LC110 Alexys HPLC system coupled to a Decade-II electrochemical detection cell and an ALF 105 50 × 1mm column with C-18 3 μm packing material (ATS Scientific, Burlington, Canada). 5-HT detection potential was 400 mV against an Ag/AgCl electrode. The mobile phase consisted 50 mM phosphoric acid, 8 mM NaCl, 0.1 mM EDTA, 500 mg/L OSA, and 13% methanol in purified, distilled water. pH was adjusted to 6.0 and solution was filtered through a 0.22 μm nylon filter. The flow rate was 65 μL/min and the detection limit for 5-HT was 0.04 nM. Chromatograms were interpreted using Clarity Chromatography software.
